# CCNA Study Note: Network Media and Cabling

This document provides a highly structured overview of physical network media types, standards, and pinning structures required for the Cisco Certified Network Associate (CCNA) curriculum.

---

## 1. Copper Cabling: Twisted-Pair Cables

Twisted-pair cabling comprises insulated copper wire pairs twisted around each other. The twist geometry uses cancellation to diminish **Electromagnetic Interference (EMI)** and **Crosstalk** (signal bleeding between neighboring wire pairs).

### Physical Variants
* **UTP (Unshielded Twisted Pair):** The predominant media architecture in commercial LANs. Lacks interior shielding, instead relying exclusively on pair twists to reject noise. Flexible, thin, and economical.
* **STP (Shielded Twisted Pair):** Contains an internal metallic foil or braided wrap enveloping the pairs. Delivers excellent isolation against heavy industrial EMI but introduces higher material costs and structural stiffness.

### UTP Standard Categories
| Category | Maximum Data Rate | Transmission Bandwidth | Maximum Segment Distance | Key Application Cases |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| **Cat 5e** | 1 Gbps | 100 MHz | 100 meters | Standard Legacy LAN Environments |
| **Cat 6** | 10 Gbps | 250 MHz | 55 meters (10G) / 100m (1G) | High-Performance Modern LANs |
| **Cat 6A** | 10 Gbps | 500 MHz | 100 meters | Server Farms / High-Density Infrastructure |

